                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d898">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">360M.1121 Devenis, Michael: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-15T14:00:00+03:00"
                            >February 15, 1941—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 15—12:14 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>285. Department’s 176, February 13, 7 p.m.<note n="26" xml:id="d898fn26">Not
                        printed; the Department asked for a report of results of efforts so far made
                        in behalf of Devenis because a “number of communications” was being received
                        inquiring about this case.</note> I am today addressing a further note to
                    the Commissariat for Foreign Affairs in the Devenis case. Thus far, I have had
                    no indication that the Soviet authorities intend to recede from their position
                    that Devenis is now a Soviet citizen irrespective of our claim that he is an
                    American citizen.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
